<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> When the fragmentary details of the Qumran texts had been assembled into a coherent sequence, what emerged was something extraordinarily similar to the chronicle of Acts, Josephus and early Christian historians. <br>
<br>
The scrolls told their own story, at the centre of which was a single protagonist, the ‘Teacher of Righteousness’- an exemplar of the same virtues associated with James. Like James, the ‘Teacher’ was the acknowledged leader of a ‘sectarian’ religious community whose members were ‘zealous for the Law’. And like James, the ‘Teacher’ had to contend with two quite separate and distinct adversaries.  <br>
<br>
One of these was dubbed the ‘Liar’ an outsider who was admitted to the community, then turned renegade, quarrelled with the ‘Teacher’ and hijacked part of the community’s doctrine and membership. According to the ‘Habakkuk Commentary’, the ‘Liar’ ‘did not listen to the word received by the Teacher of the Righteousness from the mouth of God’.<br>
<br>
Instead, he appealed to ‘the unfaithful of the New Covenant in that they have not believed in the Covenant of God and have profaned His holy name’. The text states explicitly that ‘the Liar . . . flouted the Law in the midst of their whole congregation’. He ‘led many astray’ and raised ‘a congregation on deceit’. He himself is said to be ‘pregnant with [works] of deceit’. <br>
<br>
These, of course, are precisely the transgressions of which Paul is accused in Acts – transgressions which lead, at the end of Acts, to the attempt on his life. And Eisenman stresses Paul’s striking hypersensitivity to charges of prevarication and perjury. In 1 Timothy 2:7, for example, he asserts indignantly, as if defending himself, that ‘I am telling the truth and not lie’. In II Corinthians 11:31, he swears that: ‘The God and Father of the Lord Jesus . . . knows that I am not lying.’ These are but two instances; Paul’s letters reveal an almost obsessive desire to exculpate himself from implied accusations of falsity.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> That from: (Pp. 194-195, The Dead Sea Scrolls Deception by Michael Baigent and Richard Leigh, Summit Books, New York, N.Y., 1991, ISBN: 0671734547)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
So, maybe Saul was actually a part of the Qumran/ Dead Sea Scrolls community .. but left after quarrelling about doctrine (or whatever) .. and went to Rome (also to Corinth &amp; Macedonia, apparently), where he wrote most of  the NT .. incorporating many of the doctrines &amp; ideas he’d left behind @ Qumran (following his ‘conversion’) .. and coming up with a composite ‘Christ’, based loosely on the personality/ ideas of the person referred to (in the Scrolls) as the ‘Teacher of Righteousness’ (&amp; maybe also on the various other Christs/ messiahs who were around @ the time) .. in the process incorporating elements of Roman tradition, and replacing the zealous, Jewish nationalism of the Qumran community with  a revised ‘new covenant’ that was much less threatening to Rome (and less brutal than that of the disgusting ~ from a secular/ humanist p.o.v. ~ Old Testament)? <br>
<br>
_____________<br>
Some more similarities between the Qumran Community [QC] &amp; the NT  ‘Christians’..<br>
<br>
Both the QC and NT  ‘Christians’ believed in a monotheistic God, and in a powerful ‘evil’ enemy of God.<br>
Both the QC and NT  ‘Christians’ recognised the Law of Moses.<br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC had the same particular books of scripture as favourites: Deuteronomy, Isaiah and Psalms .<br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC believed in the importance of Isaiah 40:3:  “A voice crying, In the wilderness, prepare ye the way of the Lord.”<br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC believed in the institution of a New Covenant<br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC called themselves the Poor<br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC held their property in common<br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC believed in a cosmic battle between good and evil<br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC expected the present age to end <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC believed in prophecy <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC regarded God as a king ruling a kingdom <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC believed in the expression Lord of heaven and earth (Mt 11:25; Lk 10:21).<br>
Both the QC and NT  ‘Christians’ expected an earthly messiah <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC saw God's people, the Jews, as being sinful and in need of God's forgiveness and were sure God would grant it <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC considered sacrifice in the temple of no importance <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC emphasised the purifying power of water <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC condemned divorce <br>
Both NT  ‘Christians’ and the QC used the terms &quot;Sons of Light&quot;—no one else did in Palestine at the time <br>
Both Christians and the QC had a charismatic leader,  ‘Jesus Christ’ and the Righteous Teacher <br>
